Date: Mon 31 Jul 2006
From: Pablo Nart <pablo.nart@terra.es>
Source: The Times, 27 Jul 2006 [edited]
<http://www.timesonline.co.uk/article/0,,379-2287139,00.html>

Britain prepares for threat of swamp fever
------------------------------------------
Alarming echoes of the foot and mouth disease [FMD] crisis of 5 years ago
were evident yesterday [26 Jul 2006], as British racing prepared to mount
its defenses against swamp fever, a killer disease that has already struck
9 horses in Ireland.
Limiting and monitoring equine movement between the countries is likely to
be introduced imminently, and a complete ban is not ruled out. Some Irish
racecourses are already under threat of closure. A conference call is
planned for tomorrow [28 Jul 2006], involving leading British
administrators, officials from the Department for Environment, Food and
Rural Affairs (DEFRA) and key veterinary advisers.
Urgent action is almost guaranteed. Suspending horse movements between
Britain and Ireland would temporarily cripple the lucrative breeding
industry and also poses a threat to international racing competition.
Glorious Goodwood, at which the Aidan O'Brien-trained Ad Valorem is a
possible for the showpiece Sussex Stakes, could potentially be the 1st big
meeting affected.
The disease, correctly called equine infectious anemia (EIA), which causes
fever, emaciation and usually death, is spread by biting flies and was 1st
detected in Ireland last month [June 2006]. Concern has intensified this
week with the discovery of further cases, and, last night [26 Jul 2006],
Peter Webbon, chief executive of the Horseracing Regulatory Authority
(HRA), gave some unequivocal warnings. "We have to take this seriously," he
said. "It's a very unpleasant disease, and shouldn't be confused with
equine flu, in which horses will get sick but almost always recover. If you
have an outbreak of swamp fever, you will get deaths."
In his previous role as veterinary director of the Jockey Club, Webbon was
at the coalface of the FMD epidemic in 2001, and his cool head and reasoned
thinking drew widespread praise. Yesterday [26 Jul 2006], however, there
was no mistaking his level of anxiety over the new threat: "People might
draw comparisons with FMD, but the crucial difference is that swamp fever
is a horse disease, whereas FMD is not. There is much more logic in
restricting the movement of horses in these circumstances, but I'd remind
you that the Irish stopped all horses coming into their country during FMD.
The potential threats involve horses coming over from Ireland to race and
mares returning from studs in the infected areas. The number of returning
mares will outweigh the racehorses at this time of year. We understand and
believe that the Irish have done their best to contain the infection and
imposed movement restrictions, but you have to remember that flies are no
respecters of fences, and that makes this a highly contagious situation. We
have to decide how we deal with the risk to our horse population, and we
will have contingency measures in place even before Friday's conference
call. The 2 initial options are testing -- and 2 blood tests would be
necessary to guarantee a negative -- or a veterinary declaration that each
arriving horse had been free of any possible contact. It is a changing
situation that we need to keep under constant review. I don't envisage a
complete suspension of movement yet, but that may change."
In Ireland, still more serious measures are under consideration, with a
spokesman for the Department of Agriculture confirming that the closure of
certain racecourses and sales grounds is "a possibility".
British sales companies have met with government and veterinary figures in
Ireland and requested testing procedures for all horses sent across for
auctions, beginning with the Doncaster August sale in a fortnight.
Meanwhile, it has been revealed that the outbreak began with a horse sent
for treatment at the Troytown Veterinary Hospital in Kildare, Ireland's
best-known center for sick and injured racehorses.
A horse from a stud in Co Meath was admitted in mid-June 2006 and was found
to be so sick it was quickly put down. EIA was retrospectively diagnosed,
and other horses at the center were affected. The Troytown has been closed
indefinitely while the spread of the disease is monitored.
[byline: Alan Lee]
--
Pablo Nart
<pablo.nart@terra.es>
