Source: DEFRA website [edited]
<http://www.defra.gov.uk/animalh/diseases/notifiable/disease/infectiousanaemia.htm>

Disease factsheet: equine infectious anemia, updated 27 Jul 2006
-------------------------------------------
Definition:
Infectious equine anemia (EIA) or "swamp fever" is a virus disease of
horses, which causes intermittent fever, anemia, emaciation, and death. It
can be transmitted by mechanical transfer of blood by biting insects and
occurs typically in low-lying swampy areas. The disease was 1st described
in France in 1843. The term "swamp fever" was 1st used by Torrance in 1903
in Canada, where this disease had been known before 1882.
History and spread of the disease:
Although the infectious nature of this disease had long been suspected, a
viral case was not definitely established until 1904. The virus was
classified as a retrovirus in 1976 and later grouped with the lentiviruses
(that is, non-tumor forming exogenous retroviruses) of which the human AIDS
virus is also a member.
EIA has a worldwide distribution. Early in the 20th century, serious
outbreaks occurred in France, Japan and America. During the decade 1980 to
1989, the disease was reported in many parts of America, Asia (India,
Malaysia, Myanmar, Philippines, Thailand) Europe (Austria, France, Greece,
Italy, Romania, USSR and Yugoslavia) and Australia.
Current situation:
The authorities in the Republic of Ireland (ROI) announced on 15 Jun 2006
that they had found EIA in horses on 2 stud farms. Some horses from those
stud farms, which may have been exposed to the disease, had been sent to
the UK. The State Veterinary Service acted quickly to ensure these horses
were isolated and tested for the disease. 11 horses were placed under
restrictions in England, Wales and Scotland. All of these have now tested
negative on at least one occasion and the majority on 2 occasions.
Further cases of EIA have since been confirmed in ROI, and test results are
awaited for a small number of other suspected cases. All animals involved
were previously identified and restricted as high risk due to very close
contact with an earlier confirmed case. The authorities in the ROI informed
us today on 25 Jul 2006 of 8 UK tracings subsequent to these new
confirmations. These tracings have been located, and restrictions have been
put in place with initial sampling being undertaken.
All horses that have been put under restrictions and will remain so until
DEFRA is content that they present no risk.
No cases of suspicion of EIA have been reported to DEFRA, and all testing
of any horses resident in the UK have been negative. To date, in excess of
2200 tests for EIA have now been undertaken in the ROI, with negative results.
Epidemiology:
This disease occurs in horses, mules, and donkeys. Animals may be acutely,
chronically, or subclinically affected. The incubation period varies from a
matter of days to a few months but generally is between one and 3 weeks.
Antibodies usually develop 7 to 14 days after infection and last for life.
Postmortem:
These depend upon the stage of the disease. Hemorrhages, edema, and
jaundice occur in the acute disease: enlargement of the liver, spleen and
lymph nodes are common in the chronic stage.
Control:
This is based on the restriction of movement of suspected animals and their
contacts combined with clinical observation.
